gomodel:SYNGO_3958  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: De Jong et. al demonstrate that RIM1 binds to the plasma membrane of the presynaptic active zone.\n- In STED microscopy, RIM colocalizes with Bassoon, a well established active zone marker. This colocalization is true for both endogenous RIM as well as RIM1 rescue constructs, which will be used in the remainder of the study (Figure 1 G-M)\n- The C2B domain binds to PIP2, a phospholipid that is present in the plasma membrane. The interaction is demonstrated with NMR spectroscopy, lipid cosedimentation and lipid cofloatation assays (Figure 3A-F). Additionally, a mutation is identified that abolishes PIP2 binding (Figure 4).\n- The PIP2-binding mutation in the C2B domain inhibits the function of RIM1 C2B in action-potential induced synaptic transmission (Figure 5).. Experimental description: RIM1/2 conditional knockout mice were previously described (Kaeser et al., 2011) and were maintained as homozygote lines in which the Rims1 gene (RRID:IMSR_JAX:015832 (Kaeser et al., 2008)) and the Rims2 gene (RRID:IMSR_JAX:015833 (Kaeser et al., 2011)) contained essential exons flanked by loxp sites. All animal experiments were approved by the Harvard University Animal Care and Use Committee." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2021-01-20" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_3958" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

